<h2>Great Filter</h2>
<hr>
<em>Main article: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Filter" title="Great Filter">Great Filter</a></em>
<p><br>The Great Filter, in the context of the Fermi paradox, is whatever prevents "dead matter" from giving rise, in time, to expanding, lasting life according to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kardashev_scale">Kardashev scale</a>. The most commonly agreed-upon low probability event is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abiogenesis">abiogenesis</a>: a gradual process of increasing complexity of the first self-replicating molecules by a randomly occurring chemical process. Other proposed great filters are the emergence of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eukaryotes">eukaryotes</a> or of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meiosis">meiosis</a> or some of the steps involved in the evolution of a brain capable of complex logical deductions.</p>
